column11: China met its 6.5-7% growth target in 2016. It will probably set itself a similar growth target for 2017 (The Economist). The question will be resolved according to economic and financial data from The Economist here. The question will be suspended on 31 March 2017 and will be closed when data are available in mid-April. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help. In the economics community it is reasonably well understood that China make up these statistics. The lack of variation in these numbers and the timeliness of their release tends to support this notion. In the past, the best forecasting method has been to chose a number similar to the last number and perhaps add or subtract a little to reflect the trend.

Bloomberg median average Q1 2017 forecast is 6.6% with a high of 7.1% and a low of 6.2% according to all the analysts that submit. These are widely considered to be state-controlled numbers and Beijing's target range is 6.5-7%. The number has been inside that range for the past two years. While I think the likelihood is that it prints below Q4's 6.8%, I do not think that the probability is high that it breaks below 6.5%, simply given the need for China to maintain an outward show of strength in response to the Trump administration. I skew slightly above 7% for the same reason.
It's the 6.5 INCLUSIVE part that has me putting a stronger emphasis on my top choice.

For starters, as a matter of simple math I think 7% growth rates are gone and never coming back. This is because the Chinese economy is much larger today than it was when it grew at 7% and it is much harder to get a huge relative boost at its size, even though as an absolute number the amount of growth today is far larger than it was when the Chinese economy grew faster but it's spread over a much larger economy.
I believe a lot of markets follow the pulse of Beijing. I worry they aren't compensating for the slowdown in production, construction and the enormous capital flow outwards.
I think they will make sure they hit their target.

GDP growth in China is a matter of politics, not economics (at least in the short-term). The Party needs to maintain over 6.5% to meet its growth targets, and the Party's legitimacy rests in its ability to reach these targets. Regardless of how much real economic activity is occurring, they will make up the difference with either government spending or "smoothing."
Whatever they set as the goal I think they will hit.
